            "reference": {
                "value": "6929383"
            },
            "heading": {
                "type": "heading",
                "content": "Comparatives of adjectives - 1",
                "level": 1
            },
            "items": [
                {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": "<h2> </h2>\n<p>Comparative is the name for the grammar used when comparing two things.<br/>\n<br/>\nThe two basic ways to compare are using <strong>as</strong> ... <strong>as</strong> or <strong>than</strong>. <em>She's twice <strong>as</strong> old <strong>as</strong> her sister.<br/>\nI'm almost <strong>as</strong> good in maths <strong>as</strong> in science.<br/>\nRussian is not quite <strong>as</strong> difficult <strong>as</strong> Chinese.<br/>\n<br/>\nIt's much colder today <strong>than</strong> it was yesterday.<br/>\nThis grammar topic is easier <strong>than</strong> most others.<br/>\nI find science more difficult <strong>than</strong> mathematics.</em><br/>\n<br/>\n<strong>Comparisons with <em>as ... as</em> versus comparisons with <em>than</em>:</strong><br/>\nWhen comparing with <strong>as ... as</strong>, the adjective does not change.<br/>\nWhen comparing with <strong>than</strong>, however, some changes are necessary.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://maken.wikiwijs.nl/Comparatives%20of%20adjectives.html\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://maken.wikiwijs.nl/afbeelding/p1a.png\"/></a> <a href=\"https://maken.wikiwijs.nl/Comparatives%20of%20adjectives2.html\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://maken.wikiwijs.nl/afbeelding/p2.png\"/></a> <a href=\"https://maken.wikiwijs.nl/Comparatives%20of%20adjectives3.html\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://maken.wikiwijs.nl/afbeelding/p3.png\"/></a> <a href=\"https://maken.wikiwijs.nl/Comparatives%20of%20adjectives4.html\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://maken.wikiwijs.nl/afbeelding/p4.png\"/></a></p>\n"
                }
            ],
            "sections": []
        },
        {
            "reference": {
                "value": "6929385"
            },
            "heading": {
                "type": "heading",
                "content": "Comparatives of adjectives - 2",
                "level": 1
            },
            "items": [
                {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": "<h2> </h2>\n<p>Comparing with <strong>than</strong> depends on the number of syllables the adjective has:<br/>\n<br/>\n<strong>Adjectives of one syllable:</strong><br/>\n1. syllable adjectives: add <strong>-er</strong> to the adjective<br/>\n<br/>\n<em>My sister is much tall<strong>er</strong> than me.<br/>\nIt's cold<strong>er</strong> today than it was yesterday.</em><br/>\n<br/>\n<em>Note:</em> If the word ends: consonant-vowel-consonant, then the last consonant is usually doubled in the comparative.<br/>\n<em>big - bigger, fat - fatter, hot - hotter</em><br/>\n<br/>\n<strong>Adjectives of two syllables ending in <em>-y</em>:</strong><br/>\n2. syllable adjectives ending in <strong>-y</strong>: change the <strong>-y</strong> to <strong>-ier</strong><br/>\n<br/>\n<em>She's looking happ<strong>ier</strong> today.<br/>\nThis grammar topic is eas<strong>ier</strong> than the last one.<br/>\nWhy is everyone else luck<strong>ier</strong> than me?</em></p>\n"
                }
            ],
            "sections": []
        },
        {
            "reference": {
                "value": "6929387"
            },
            "heading": {
                "type": "heading",
                "content": "Comparatives of adjectives - 3",
                "level": 1
            },
            "items": [
                {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": "<h2> </h2>\n<p><em>Beware:</em> Do not confuse adjectives and adverbs.<br/>\n2-syllable adverbs ending in <strong>-y</strong> must be compared with the word <strong>more</strong>.<br/>\n<br/>\n<em>I drive more quickly (quicklier) than my brother.</em></p>\n<p><strong>Other adjectives with two syllables:</strong><br/>\nOther 2-syllable adjectives: use <strong>more</strong> with the unchanged adjective<br/>\n<br/>\n<em>The shops are always <strong>more</strong> crowded just before Christmas.<br/>\nIs there anything <strong>more</strong> boring than reading about grammar?<br/>\nMy sister is <strong>more</strong> careful with her writing than I am with mine.</em><br/>\n<br/>\n<em>Exceptions to this rule</em><br/>\nThe comparative of some shorter 2-syllable adjectives can be formed with <strong>-er</strong>.<br/>\n- simple - simpl<strong>er</strong><br/>\n- clever - clever<strong>er</strong><br/>\n- narrow - narrow<strong>er</strong></p>\n<p>To be sure which comparative method to use, you will need to consult a good dictionary.</p>\n"
                }
            ],
            "sections": []
        },
        {
            "reference": {
                "value": "6929389"
            },
            "heading": {
                "type": "heading",
                "content": "Comparatives of adjectives - 4",
                "level": 1
            },
            "items": [
                {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": "<h2> </h2>\n<p><strong>Adjectives with three syllables or more:</strong><br/>\nAdjectives with 3 or more syllables: use more with the unchanged adjective<br/>\n<br/>\n<em>Russian grammar is <strong>more difficult</strong> than English grammar.</em><br/>\n<em>My sister is much <strong>more intelligent</strong> than me.</em><br/>\n<em>I find maths lessons <strong>more enjoyable</strong> than science lessons.</em></p>\n<p><strong>Formal forms of the pronouns after comparisons:</strong><br/>\nMany educated English speakers prefer to use the Subject form of Pronouns plus a verb rather than the Object form without a Verb in comparative sentences, especially in formal situations.<br/>\nThey say, for example, <em>My sister is taller <strong>than I am</strong>.</em><br/>\nThe alternative, omitting the verb as in the following examples, is considered to be even more formal and is avoided by most British English speakers: <em>My sister is taller <strong>than I</strong></em>.</p>\n"
                }
            ],
            "sections": []
